INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5f936d00-4e25-41f3-8367-cfd28958e0fd',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Ruby Type Safety — Sorbet Signatures Without the Boilerplate$escape$,
  $escape$Ruby is dynamically typed, but that doesn't mean you're flying blind. Sorbet brings gradual static typing via `sig` blocks that are checked at both runtime and statically with `srb tc`. Unlike generics in Java or Rust, Ruby leans on parameterized types through `T::Array[Integer]` and `T::Hash[Symbol, String]` — composable, readable, and enforced only where you opt in.

The `T.nilable` wrapper makes null safety explicit: `T.nilable(String)` forces callers to handle `nil` rather than discovering it in production. Combined with `T.must()`, you assert non-nil at a boundary and get a runtime raise if violated — better than a cryptic NoMethodError three frames deep.

For duck typing purists, `T::Struct` and interfaces via `T::Props` give you shape-based contracts without abandoning idiomatic Ruby. Sorbet's `# typed: strict` mode pushes you toward fully annotated files, while `# typed: false` lets legacy code coexist. The incremental adoption model is why Stripe shipped it across millions of Ruby lines without a rewrite.$escape$,
  $escape$# typed: strict

class UserService
  extend T::Sig

  sig { params(ids: T::Array[Integer]).returns(T::Hash[Integer, String]) }
  def fetch_names(ids)
    User.where(id: ids).pluck(:id, :name).to_h
  end

  sig { params(user: T.nilable(User)).returns(String) }
  def display_name(user)
    T.must(user).name
  end
end$escape$,
